# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bristol-type-603
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with an annual household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low rate of air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow by between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona; Hong Kong; China; Japan; and Italy.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Costs of health care can act as another barrier: the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and has encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] The Chinese inventor Ding Huan (1st century CE) of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning.
[src:bristol-type-603/air-conditioning] In the nations of Europe where the technology is relatively unadopted, the strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The **Audi A4** is a line of luxury compact executive cars produced from 1994 to 2025 by the German car manufacturer Audi, a subsidiary of the Volkswagen Group.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4 has been built in five generations and is based on the Volkswagen Group B platform.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The first generation A4 succeeded the Audi 80.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The automaker's internal numbering treats the A4 as a continuation of the Audi 80 lineage, with the initial A4 designated as the B5-series, followed by the B6, B7, B8, and the B9.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B8 and B9 versions of the A4 are built on the Volkswagen Group MLB platform shared with several models and brands across the Volkswagen Group.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Audi A4 automobile layout consists of a front-engine design, with transaxle-type transmissions mounted at the rear of the engine.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The cars are front-wheel drive, or on some models, "quattro" all-wheel drive.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4 is available as a sedan and station wagon.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Historically, the second (B6) and third generations (B7) of the A4 also included a convertible version.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] For the B8 and B9 versions, the convertible, along with a new coupé and 5-door liftback variant, was spun-off by Audi into a new nameplate called the Audi A5.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It has been manufactured in Ingolstadt since its beginning, in Changchun China by FAW-VW since 2003 and in Aurangabad India by Audi India since 2007.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B9 generation A4 and A5 will be replaced by B10 version of A5, as part of Audi's new naming convention.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The first generation Audi A4 (known internally as the ***Typ* 8D**) debuted in October 1994, with production starting November 1994 and European sales commencing in January 1995 for the 1995 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] North American sales later began in September 1995 for the 1996 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It was built on the Volkswagen Group B5 (PL45) platform, which it shared with the fourth generation Volkswagen Passat (B5, *Typ* 3B).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It had a front-mounted longitudinal engine and front-wheel drive.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Many variations of the A4 were also available with Audi's quattro four-wheel drive system.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4 was initially introduced as a four-door saloon/sedan; the Avant (estate/wagon) was introduced in November 1995 and went on sale in February 1996.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Development began in 1988, with the first design sketches being created later that year.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] By 1991, an exterior design by Imre Hasanic was chosen and frozen for November 1994 production by 1992.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The interior design was later finalized in 1992, with pilot production commencing in the first half of 1994.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Development concluded in the third quarter of 1994, preceding November 1994 start of production.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A wide range of engines were available in European markets, between 1.6 and 2.8 litres for petrol engines; and a 1.9-litre diesel engine available with Volkswagen Group's VE technology, capable of achieving a 90 PS (66 kW; 89 bhp) or 110 PS (81 kW; 108 bhp).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The 2.6 and 2.8-litre V6 engines which had been carried over from the old 80/90 proved popular, although in North America, the 2.8-litre engine was the only V6 that was available there until 1997.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A 2.4-liter version was developed especially for the Thai market, where import duty jumped from 60 to 100 percent on cars of over 2,400 cc displacement.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Audi A4 was the first model in the Volkswagen Group to feature the new 1.8-litre 20v engine with five valves per cylinder, based on the unit Audi Sport had developed.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A turbocharged 1.8T version produced 150 PS (110 kW; 148 bhp) and 210 N⋅m (155 lb⋅ft) torque.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Moreover, a quattro GmbH special edition of the B5 1.8T was later available in Germany and Europe, for which the engine's power output was raised to 180 PS (132 kW; 178 bhp) and 235 N⋅m (173 lb⋅ft).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi also debuted their new tiptronic automatic transmission on the B5 platform, based on the unit Porsche developed for their 964-generation 911.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The transmission is a conventional automatic gearbox with a torque converter offering the driver a fully-automatic operation or manual selection of the gear ratios.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B5 marked Audi's continued move into the midsize luxury car segment, having started this trajectory notably with later model years of the preceding Audi 80/90 B4.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Despite initial mechanical problems, overall build and assembly quality were lauded both by the automotive press and within Audi and Volkswagen, and at the time, parent company Volkswagen declared the B5 the company-wide build quality benchmark for all its other models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Audi A4 B5 saw nearly constant minor changes and alterations throughout its seven-year run.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Moreover, a significant facelift was introduced for the 1998 B5 model year at the 1997 Frankfurt Motor Show, with sales beginning in Europe in early 1998.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The 2.8-litre 30-valve V6 engine replaced the 2.8-litre 12-valve.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A 2.5-litre V6 Turbocharged Direct Injection diesel engine with 150 PS (110 kW; 148 bhp) was standard on the Quattro.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A six-speed manual gearbox was available, as well as the new high-performance Audi S4, now part of the A4 lineup (the previous S4 had been an Audi 100).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Cosmetic updates included new rear lights, headlights, door handles, and another minor exterior/interior changes.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In mid-1998, the 1.8 20vT engine available outside Europe had its power output raised to 170 PS (125 kW; 168 bhp).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The previous KKK K03 turbocharger, although fundamentally unchanged, received revisions on the turbine side to prevent cracking due to heat.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The 12-valve V6 was replaced by the 30-valve unit which had been available in Europe for two years.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A further facelift took place across the A4 and S4 platform in February 1999 as a 1999.5 model; changes were largely cosmetic but affected many components, such as both front and rear bumpers, the front and rear lights, the center console, and door handles.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] While outer body shell changes from the pre-facelift model were superficially subtle, it meant that no two body panels were directly interchangeable between each other.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] This facelift was known at Audi as a *Grosse Produktaufwertung* (*Major Product Upgrade*), as was also signified by facelift cars now carrying the denomination "8D**2**".
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In 1999 Audi also debuted an even higher performance ***R**enn**S**port* model (rennsport translates as *racing sport*), the RS4 Avant, like its predecessor RS2, available only in the Avant bodystyle.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In the Euro NCAP safety and crash tests, the Audi B5 A4 received 3 stars for front- and side-impact protection, but the last star is flagged to indicate that the driver may be subjected to a high risk of chest injury in the side impact.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In 1997, Audi was the first European car manufacturer to put a hybrid vehicle into mass production, the third generation Audi duo, then based on the A4 Avant.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The next A4, internally designated ***Typ* 8E**, debuted on 10 October 2000, now riding on the Volkswagen Group B6 (PL46) platform.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The car's new styling was developed under Peter Schreyer between 1996 and 1998, inspired by the Bauhaus design language of the C5 (second-generation) Audi A6 introduced in 1997.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The 1.6-litre base model powerplant remained unchanged, but most other petrol/gasoline engines received either displacement increases, or power upgrades.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] This generation of quattro consisted of default of 50:50 front to rear dynamic torque distribution.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A Bosch ESP 5.7 Electronic Stability Programme (ESP) system, with anti-lock braking system (ABS), brake assist, and electronic brakeforce distribution (EBD) were standard across the range.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] For 2002, Audi increased power in the 1.8 Turbo engines to 183 PS (135 kW; 180 bhp) and 190 PS (140 kW; 187 bhp) – the 190 PS variant designated by a red 'T' on the boot lid.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Available with four wheel drive and in the 2.5 TDI intermediate version to 163 PS (120 kW; 161 bhp).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A 2.0 engine with Fuel Stratified Injection (FSI) was also available.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A year later, Audi reintroduced the S4, now powered by a 344 PS (253 kW; 339 bhp) 4.2 L V8 engine, as well as an A4 Cabriolet convertible variant (***Typ* 8H**), finally replacing the 80-based Audi Cabriolet which had been discontinued in 2000.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It included an electro-hydraulic operated roof, which lowered in under 30 seconds and incorporated some styling changes, such as body-coloured lower bumper and sill panels, which later found their way to the saloon version.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Audi A4 Cabriolet version was co-developed and manufactured by Karmann.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi introduced a continuously variable transmission developed by LuK, named multitronic, which replaced the dated conventional automatic transmission on front-wheel drive models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] There have been widespread complaints from consumers around the world that the transmission box is prone to electronic glitches as well as mechanical problems.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Borrowing from the Audi A6, the boot was redesigned to remove the extension of the top edge with a smoother fold line.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The rear light assemblies now formed part of the top line, these styling cues were eventually borrowed by other European as well as Asian manufacturers.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A sport package named 'Ultra Sport' was introduced in the North American market shortly before the B6 was replaced by the B7.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It included aluminium interior trim and door sills, "S line" steering wheel, front and rear spoilers, side skirts, and quattro GmbH designed 18-inch RS4 alloy wheels.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) awarded both the B6 & B7 a "Good" rating in the frontal crash test; the B7 was not retested since the front portion is structurally the same.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi introduced a heavily facelifted A4 in late 2004, with the internal designation of **B7**.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The front grille assembly changed to a tall trapezoidal shape in the same manner as the C6 (third-generation) Audi A6; however, the dashboard and interior were virtually unchanged from the B6 aside from minor detailing.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi's internal platform nomenclature uses PL46 (**p**assenger car **l**ongitudinal platform, size **4**, generation **6**) for both B6 and B7 chassis.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The ***Typ* 8E** and ***Typ* 8H** internal designations are also carried over from the B6 A4 range, but now have an additional identifying suffix – 8EC for the saloon, 8ED for the Avant, and 8HE for the Cabriolet.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The engine lineup received many additions.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The 2005 introduction of Fuel Stratified Injection (FSI) on the 2.0 TFSI and 3.2 V6 FSI petrol/gasoline engines, as well as other refinements, increased power output to 200 PS (147 kW; 197 bhp) and 255 PS (188 kW; 252 bhp), respectively.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] These engines both use a four-valve per cylinder configuration.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The prior 5-valve design was incompatible with the FSI direct injection system (due to the siting of the fuel injector, now discharging directly into the combustion chamber).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Torsen T-2 based quattro permanent four-wheel drive remained as an option on most A4 models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi retained the 5 speed manual transmission with the 1.9 TDI and 2.0 non turbo petrol engines while introducing the 6 speed manual for all higher output variants.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] As before, multitronic continuously variable transmission (CVT), now with selectable 'seven-speeds', was an option on front-wheel drive models, whilst a conventional ZF 6HP 6-speed tiptronic automatic transmission was an option on the quattro four-wheel drive models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Another inclusion on the RS4 was the latest generation Torsen T-3 Quattro 4WD system, which uses a 'default' asymmetric 40:60 front-rear dynamic torque distribution bias.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] This new asymmetric center differential was initially only available on the RS4 but was added a year later on the S4.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The remainder of the B7 A4 range still used the T-2 50:50 default dynamic split center diff.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A variant, developed by quattro GmbH, was first introduced in May 2005, named "Audi A4 DTM Edition".
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It was inspired by Audi's race cars of the 2004 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters and was reintroduced in 2006 as a regular option.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The 2.0T FSI engine received revised software mapping to the ECU, which increased the output to 220 PS (162 kW; 217 bhp) and 300 N⋅m (221 lb⋅ft) of torque.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It was available with front-wheel drive, or Quattro four-wheel drive.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B7 Cabriolet model arrived later than the other two body variants, being first shown in late 2005 and with sales beginning in February 2006.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] New on the Cabriolet was an entry-level 2.0 TDI version, which was not offered with the Multitronic CVT gearbox.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Cabriolet version was produced by Karmann until February 2009.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It also had a power increase of 20 PS, giving an output of 220 PS on the 2.0T model.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] According to 2007 Swedish vehicle inspection data, the Audi A4 Avant with diesel engine is the most reliable vehicle available on the market, with vehicle inspection rejection rate of 0.0% in three-year-old category.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] When the successor B8 A4 range was introduced, the B7 series A4 was restyled and rebadged as the SEAT Exeo in 2008 with changes to the front and rear plus interior trim from the A4 Cabriolet.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The entire Audi B7 A4 production line from Audi's Ingolstadt plant was dismantled and sent to Volkswagen Group's SEAT factory in Martorell, Spain.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In 2005 only available as **DTM Edition**.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] From summer 2006 on available for all saloon and Avant.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] There were two different versions – one had an 8 valve cylinder head the other had 16 valves.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] They had the same power and torque output and performed equally.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Customers could not choose directly between those two engines.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] They got the 8-valve version when they ordered the DPF otherwise they got the 16-valve version (BRE engine code).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In many countries the DPF became standard equipment for all B7 diesel engines from model year 2006 on and the 8-valve engine was no more.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In 2006 replaced by the 2.7 V6 TDI engine.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In 2006 replaced by a stronger version of the same engine.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Audi A4 offered several standard safety features, including Bosch ESP 8.0 Electronic Stability Programme (ESP) with anti-lock braking system (ABS), side airbags in the seats, 'sideguard' curtain airbags, and its optional quattro four-wheel drive system.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It also received the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) "Top Safety Pick For 2007".
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] EuroNCAP crash test results from the B6 apply to the B7 model.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi released the first official pictures of the B8 series A4 in August 2007 and unveiled the car to the public at the September 2007 Frankfurt Motor Show.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Saloon/sedan and Avant (estate/wagon) models are offered.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Avant was unveiled to the public at the March 2008 Geneva Motor Show.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] For North America's destined models, the B8 continued in production for the 2016 model year, while Europe began deliveries on the 2016 B9 model.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B8 A4 is built on a variant of the Audi Modular Longitudinal Platform, a platform that is also used in the Audi A5 coupé.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] While prior A4 chassis were limited in wheelbase due to the relationship between the engine, transmission and front axle, the MLP allows for a reduced front overhang, resulting in a greater wheelbase length without the same increase in overall length.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] This effectively redistributes the centre of gravity slightly rearwards, improving handling by better balancing vehicle mass between the front and rear axles.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The estimated static front:rear weight ratio of the B8 A4 is approximately 55:45, depending on body style and engine.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The relocation of the steering rack in front of the axle also improves handling over previous A4 platforms.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Key to the implementation of MLP is the novel mounting of the differential in front of the clutch.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] This is achieved by driving the flywheel/clutch remotely by means of a 'top hat' shaped drive plate, between which the differential lay shaft passes, whilst power transmission to the final drive is via an inclined transfer shaft which runs the length of the transmission unit.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Whilst the platform retains Audi's "overhung" engine mounting position, the front axle is now 152mm further forward than the previous B6/B7 generation platform.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The transfer shaft, however, has the effect of creating a large "bulge" on one side of the transmission tunnel, which on right-hand drive versions forces the pedals to be badly offset, which has attracted criticism from the British motoring press in particular.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B8 A4 has increased in wheelbase by 160 millimetres (6.3 in) and in length by 117 millimetres (4.6 in) over the prior B7, which has allowed for increased rear seating legroom.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Although the overall dimensions have increased, the curb weight has dropped some 10%.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The boot (trunk) has also increased to 480 litres (17.0 cu ft) for the saloon (sedan) version.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4 Avant will have a maximum capacity of 1,430 L (50.5 cu ft) with the rear seats folded down.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Reception has been mixed, with praise for the Audi A4's increased size, giving it best-in-class rear legroom and trunk space in the compact executive car segment.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Its inline-4 2.0 TFSI engine, while efficient providing plenty of torque, was considered lacking and less refined compared to 6-cylinder engines of lighter rivals who posted faster acceleration times.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] However, the Audi S4 sports sedan has been well-received for its V6 3.0 TFSI engine's power and efficiency.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] During a model, cycle changes are made to integrate new technologies and to keep the model competitive.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] These changes are referenced based on the model year (MY) of the car.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In Australia, the B8 has undergone 2 revisions leading to three variants, the B8, B8 MY10 and B8 MY11.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Avant station wagon/estate was presented at the March 2008 Geneva Motor Show.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The **A4 Allroad Quattro** is based upon the Avant but features a wider track, increased ground clearance, Quattro permanent four-wheel drive, a distinctive radiator grille, stainless steel underbody guards and roof rails.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4 allroad quattro was made available in early summer 2009.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The car was unveiled in 2009 Geneva Motor Show.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4L is a long-wheelbase version of the sedan/saloon for the Chinese market, with a 60 mm (2.4 in) longer wheelbase and length.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The vehicle was presented at the 2008 Guangzhou Motor Show.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The production version then went on sale in January 2009.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Launch models included a 2.0 TFSI with 132 kW (177 hp) and the 3.2 FSI with 195 kW (261 hp).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4-based convertible models were replaced by the A5/S5 Cabriolet.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B8 powertrain options are the following: engines, transmissions and drivelines: (All United Kingdom specification unless stated otherwise).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The quattro permanent four-wheel drive system uses the latest Torsen T-3 centre differential, with a default 40:60 front to rear asymmetric torque distribution ratio (used first on the B7 RS4) as standard.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] (Previous A4 Quattro models split torque with a default front:rear 50:50).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The additional torque bias applied to the rear wheels helps mimic the driving dynamics of rear-wheel drive cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Audi was reported to stop offering 3.2L V6 models in 2010 model year, but still offers them as of August 2011 (Germany).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] All petrol engines use Fuel Stratified Injection (FSI), and all diesel engines use the common rail fuel delivery (with a pressure of 1,600 bars (23,000 psi)), with piezo injectors of their Turbocharged Direct Injection engines.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In 2009, Audi announced the seven-speed S-Tronic dual-clutch automatic transmission as an option for A4 in the UK and European markets.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] All A4L models include Speed 8 multitronic continuously variable/manual transmission, except for A4L 3.2 FSI quattro, which includes Tiptronic automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Volkswagen settled a class-action lawsuit in 2013 involving the failures of the CVT transmission in its Audi A4 and A6 automobiles for model years 2002–2006.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It includes a common rail 1,968 cc (120 cu in) TDI diesel engine rated at 120 PS (88 kW; 118 hp) and 290 N⋅m (214 lb⋅ft), a stop-start system and regenerative braking.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It can achieve a fuel consumption of 3.99L/100 km (58.95 mpg) and CO2 output of 105 g/km.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It can accelerate from 0-100 km/h (62 mph) in 10.7 seconds, with a top speed of 206 km/h (128 mph).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Other features include electric motor-based power steering, revised aerodynamics, low-rolling-resistance 225/45R17 tires, and electric actuation of the rear brakes.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The car was unveiled in Paris Motor Show.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The facelift model of the Audi A4 was released in 2012 for the 2013 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] It features redesigned LED headlamps and taillights, front air dam with fog lamps, and closely set twin exhausts.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Interior changes include Bluetooth connectivity for audio streaming (nav equipped models only) and a redesigned ignition key.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Controls for air-conditioning, infotainment, and power windows gain chrome clasps.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The A4 includes a radio with eight speakers as standard, while the MMI navigation system with voice dialogue is optional.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] A new "Drive Select System" allows drivers to choose comfort, dynamic, individual, or efficiency modes for fuel-efficiency.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The power output of the 1.8 TFSI engine is 170 bhp and 320 Nm of torque – up 10 bhp and 70 Nm from the previous versions.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Electromechanical power steering is standard.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Trim levels are Attraction, Ambition, and Ambiente.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] In the UK, the A4 range is offered in SE, SE Technik, Technik, S line, and Black Edition model grades.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] All-wheel-drive Quattro is offered in most engine and grade combinations.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] For North America, the facelift model Audi A4 sedan is only offered with a 2.0 TFSI turbocharged inline-4 gasoline engine, while the performance upgrade remains the Audi S4 with a 3.0 TFSI supercharged V6 gasoline engine, and no diesel engines were offered.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] Model grades are Premium, Premium Plus, and Prestige.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The Avant was discontinued, leaving the Allroad Quattro as the only station wagon body style.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] For the 2016 model year, the A4 and S4 continued in B8 production.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p01] The B9 A4 would not reach the North American market until the 2017 model year, while the S4 variant would not be available until the 2018 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The fifth-generation of the A4 was revealed in June 2015 when pre-production versions were released to the motoring press, with the official launch occurring at the Frankfurt Motor Show in September 2015.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] It is commonly referred to as the **B9**, representing the ninth generation of the Audi 80/A4 series, which were originally (but no longer) based on the B platform.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The B9 is slightly larger than the outgoing B8, but Audi claims the new A4 is around 120 kg (265 lb) lighter than its predecessor due to the use of its new lightweight aluminum-hybrid construction.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The B9 also comes with several A4 firsts such as virtual cockpit, Apple CarPlay and Android Auto, full-color head-up display, and Audi pre-sense.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] A common misconception is that the B9 (or 8W) generation started in model year 2017, as that is when the US market got it – however, it was available in European markets beginning in 2015.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Audi A4 launched with three petrol and four diesel engines.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] US models received only the gasoline versions which consisted of the base 2.0L turbo found in the ultra model, the standard 2.0L turbo in the standard grades, and the V6 engines offered in the S4 and RS4 (3.0L and 2.9L respectively).
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Ultra introduced Audi's new high efficiency variant of the EA888 that achieves best in class fuel economy through the use of an increased compression ratio engine (9.6:1 to 11.7:1) with shorter compression and longer-expansion phases.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] It sends this power through a 7-Speed dual-clutch powering the front wheels only.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] This allows the A4 to achieve an EPA rating of 27 city/37 highway/31 combined.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] This variant was only offered until 2020 at which point it was rebranded to the 40 TFSI.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Performance figures are shown under the engine variants below.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Available model grades are Premium, Premium Plus, Ultra Premium, Ultra Premium Plus and Prestige.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Ultra models featured improved fuel efficiency and reduced emissions, and were only available in the FWD configuration.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Every other model was available in either FWD or Quattro.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The S Line and Black Optic packages were also made available.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The S Line package uses skirts, bumpers, seats and wheels from the Audi S4, and adds an aluminum inlay to the interior consoles.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Black Optic package, or Black Edition, also uses the S4's body kit, but replaces the exterior's chrome trim with black counterparts.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] A slight facelift was introduced in 2019, featuring new front and rear bumpers inspired by the Audi RS 4.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Additionally, the Titanium model grade was introduced to replace the Ultra Premium and Ultra Premium Plus models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The facelift model, also known as the **B9.5**, was made available in 2020.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] It brought the A4's aesthetic in line with the S4, A6, A7 and A8.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] In addition to redesigned headlights and taillights, almost every body panel on the A4 was altered, with only the hood, trunk and roof remaining untouched.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Notably, the character line that ran the length of the A4 was removed, with creases added to the front and rear fenders in its place.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] While the interior was largely untouched, the mechanical controls for the infotainment center were replaced with a touchscreen and larger display.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Following the facelift, the A4 and S4 now share their body panels, with their grilles and badges being the only external distinctions between the models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Post-facelift, the Titanium model was removed from production, leaving only the Premium, Premium Plus and Prestige model grades.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Additionally, US delivered Post-facelift A4's are only available in the Quattro configuration.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Whereas front wheel drive continued to be available for the rest of the world.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Noting that the B9.5 introduced Quattro-Ultra technology, a system which can disconnect the all wheel drive to save fuel during specific driving conditions, thus negating the disadvantage of Quattro's additional fuel consumption.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Black Optic and S Line packages also return for select models.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Black Optic package can be equipped on any Premium Plus or Prestige Model, while the S Line model can be applied to any Premium Plus or Prestige Model with a 45 TFSI engine.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The S Line package makes no changes to the exterior beyond its badging, as the A4 and S4 now share their body kits.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] It instead provides an aluminum inlay for the interior, improved seats, and stainless steel pedals.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] In addition to the above packages, Audi also manufactures aftermarket accessories for the A4, including decals, spoilers, mirror caps and tail pipes.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The 2025 model year marks the final production year for the Audi A4 nameplate after nearly three decades in the market, with the model being discontinued and replaced by the redesigned Audi A5 as part of the company's restructured naming convention.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Under Audi's new nomenclature system, odd-numbered models designate internal combustion engine vehicles while even-numbered models are reserved for electric vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] For 2025, Audi streamlined the A4 lineup by eliminating the 40 TFSI trim level, leaving only the 45 TFSI variant with a 261-horsepower turbocharged 2.0-liter four-cylinder engine paired with a 12-volt mild hybrid system.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Updates for the final model year include remote engine start via the myAudi app as standard equipment across all trims, and HomeLink smart home control buttons relocated to the rearview mirror.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Premium Plus trim received Audi's Navigation Plus package as standard equipment, while the Convenience package for the Premium trim added rear USB charge ports.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] A new S Line Plus package became available for Premium Plus and Prestige trims, featuring black exterior trim, dark exhaust tips, 19-inch wheels, red brake calipers, leather-and-faux-suede seats, carbon fiber interior trim, and stainless-steel pedal caps.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] All 2025 A4 models come standard with Audi's quattro all-wheel drive system and a seven-speed dual-clutch automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The infotainment system features a 10.1-inch touchscreen, with the Premium Plus trim offering an upgraded Bang & Olufsen audio system with 19 speakers and Audi's Virtual Cockpit digital gauge display.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Three trim levels are offered: Premium S line starting at $44,100, Premium Plus S line at $48,600, and Prestige S line at $51,300.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The A4 allroad wagon variant continues for 2025 with a 2.0-liter turbocharged four-cylinder engine producing 261-horsepower and 273 lb-ft of torque, featuring standard adaptive damping suspension and Audi drive select system.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Seven engines are available from launch, three petrol, and four diesel.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] All are available in both the A4 Saloon and A4 Avant.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The figures below are for the saloon only.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The 2017 Audi A4 earned Good ratings across the board for Crashworthiness and Seat belts & child restraints.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] For Crash avoidance & mitigation it earned a Marginal to Acceptable for headlights depending on trim as well as Goods across the board for Front crash prevention vehicle-to-vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] These ratings apply to the full B9 A4 line and the mechanically similar A5 Sportback.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The Audi A4 released to Europe in 2015 for the 2016 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] It earned a 5-Star Rating for all A4s, A5 Coupes, and A5 Sportbacks.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] These ratings were valid through January 2022 at which point they expire.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Audi Sport re-entered the Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters (DTM) series in 2004 (after having privateer teams run the Abt Sportsline Audi TT-R) with a V8 engined silhouette racing car resembling the A4 saloon, known as the **Audi A4 DTM**.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] A4 DTM cars are identified by Audi Sport "R"-prefix designations.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Brad Jones won the Australian Super Touring Championship in both 1996 and 1998 driving an A4.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The A4 was used in the 1996–1998 and 2011–2015 British Touring Car Championship seasons.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The A4 was used in the 2000–2001 European Super Touring Championship season.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] A4 drivers won the Italian Superturismo Championship in 1995 and 1996.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] Drivers in an A4 won 2001, 2002, 2003, and the 2006 Swedish Touring Car Championship season.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The A4 was entered into the 1995 Super Tourenwagen Cup season.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The car was used in the 2006 Russian Circuit Racing Series.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] The A4 was used in the SCCA World Challenge for several years.
[src:bristol-type-603/audi-a4-p02] In March 2023, Audi CEO Markus Duesmann did confirm that the A4 would be renamed the A5, while the A6 would become the A7, with the future A4 and A6 to be sold as electric vehicles only.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:bristol-type-603/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Many emergency vehicles have distinctive lighting equipment to warn drivers of their presence.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Early road vehicles used fuelled lamps before the availability of electric lighting.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The first Ford Model T used carbide lamps for headlights and oil lamps for tail lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] It did not have all-electric lighting as a standard feature until several years after its introduction.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Dynamos for automobile headlights were first fitted around 1908 and became commonplace in 1920s automobiles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Trafficators—signalling arms that flipped up, which later were lighted—were introduced in the early 1900s, and were actuated either mechanically or pneumatically.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Tail lights and brake lights were introduced around 1915, and by 1919, low-beam or dipped beam headlights were available.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Sealed beam headlights were introduced in 1936 and standardized as the only acceptable type in the US in 1940.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Self-cancelling turn signals were developed in 1940.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] By 1945, headlights and signal lights were integrated into the body styling.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Halogen headlights were developed in Europe in 1960.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] High-intensity discharge (HID) headlights were produced starting in 1991.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] In 1993, the first LED tail lights were installed on mass-production automobiles, with LED headlights subsequently being introduced in the 2000s as more powerful LEDs became available.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The colour of light emitted by vehicle lights is largely standardized by established conventions, first codified in the 1949 Geneva Convention on Road Traffic and later specified in the 1968 United Nations Vienna Convention on Road Traffic.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] With some regional exceptions, lights facing rearward must emit red light, side-facing lights and all turn signals must emit amber light, and lights facing forward must emit white or selective yellow light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] No other colours are permitted except on emergency vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Vehicle lighting colour specifications can differ somewhat in countries that have not signed the 1949 and/or 1968 Conventions; examples include turn signals and side marker lights in North America, as described in those lights' sections later in this article.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Forward illumination is provided by high- ("main", "full", "driving") and low- ("dip", "dipped", "passing") beam headlights, which may be augmented by auxiliary fog lights, driving lights, or cornering lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Low beam (also called dipped beam, passing beam, or meeting beam) headlights provide adequate forward and lateral illumination without dazzling other road users with excessive glare.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] This beam is specified for use whenever other vehicles are present ahead.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE regulations for dipped beam headlights specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is flat and low, while the half of the beam closest to the outside of the road slopes up and towards the near side of the roadway.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] This permits a functional compromise where it is possible to substantially prevent glare for oncoming drivers, while still allowing adequate illumination for drivers to see pedestrians, road signs, hazards, etc. on their side of the road.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The United States and Canada use proprietary FMVSS / CMVSS standards instead of UN ECE regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] These standards contain regulations for dipped beam headlights that also specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is also flat and low, but not as low as prescribed in UN ECE regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The half of the beam closest to the outside of the road is also flat, but higher than the half closest to oncoming vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] This results in substantially increased glare for oncoming drivers and also poorer illumination of the near side of the roadway in comparison to headlights conforming to UN ECE regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] High beam (also called main beam, driving beam, or full beam) headlights provide an intense, centre-weighted distribution of light with no particular glare control.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Therefore, they are only suitable for use when alone on the road, as the glare they produce will dazzle other drivers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE Regulations permit higher-intensity high-beam headlights than allowed under U.S. and Canadian FMVSS / CMVSS standards.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Auxiliary high beam lights may be fitted to provide high-intensity light to enable the driver to see at longer range than the vehicle's high beam headlights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Such lights are most notably fitted on rally cars, and are occasionally fitted to production vehicles derived from or imitating such cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] They are common in countries with large stretches of unlit roads, or in regions such as the Nordic countries that receive fewer daylight hours during winter.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] "Driving light" is a term hailing from the early days of night time driving, when it was relatively rare to encounter an opposing vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Only on occasions when opposing drivers passed each other would the low (dipped or "passing") beam be used.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The high beam was therefore known as the "driving beam", and this terminology is still found in international UN Regulations, which do not distinguish between a vehicle's primary (mandatory) and auxiliary (optional) upper/driving beam lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The "driving light" term has been supplanted in US regulations by the functionally descriptive term "auxiliary high-beam light".
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Many countries regulate the installation and use of driving lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] For example, in Russia, each vehicle may have no more than three pairs of driving lights (including the original lights), and in Paraguay, auxiliary driving lights must be off and covered with opaque material when the vehicle is operated in urban areas.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Front fog lights provide a wide, bar-shaped beam of light with a sharp cutoff at the top, and are generally aimed and mounted low.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] They may produce white or selective yellow light, and were designed for use at low speed to increase the illumination directed towards the road surface and verges in conditions of poor visibility due to fog, dust or snow.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] They are sometimes used in place of dipped-beam headlights, reducing glare from fog or falling snow, although the legality of using front fog lights without low-beam headlights varies by jurisdiction.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] In most countries, weather conditions rarely necessitate the use of front fog lights and there is no legal requirement for them, so their primary purpose is frequently cosmetic.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] They are often available as optional extras or only on higher trim levels of many cars.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Since as early as the 2020s, several car manufacturers have noticeably omitted the front fog lights from many of their latest models, as more recent high-tech lighting technologies such as daytime running lamps (DRLs) and LEDs connected to automatic high-beam systems negate the use of fog lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] However, some manufacturers who still offer fog lights as standard equipment in certain model trims have diversified its use to function also as an automatic lighting delay for vehicles, to light up surroundings and roadside curbs after being parked.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] An SAE study has shown that in the United States, more people inappropriately use their fog lights in dry weather than use them properly in poor weather.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] The respective purposes of front fog lights and driving lights are often confused, due in part to the misconception that fog lights are always selective yellow, while any auxiliary light that makes white light is a driving light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Automakers and aftermarket parts and accessories suppliers frequently refer interchangeably to "fog lights" and "driving lights" (or "fog/driving lights").
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] On some models, cornering lights provide steady-intensity white light for lateral illumination in the direction of an intended turn or lane change.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] They are generally actuated in conjunction with the turn signals, and they may be wired to also illuminate when the vehicle is shifted into reverse gear.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Some modern vehicles activate the cornering light on one or the other side when the steering wheel input reaches a predetermined angle in that direction, regardless of whether a turn signal has been activated.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] American technical standards contain provisions for front cornering lights as well as rear cornering lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Cornering lights have traditionally been prohibited under international UN Regulations, though provisions have recently been made to allow them as long as they are only operable when the vehicle is travelling at less than 40 kilometres per hour (about 25 mph).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p01] Police cars, emergency vehicles, and vehicles competing in road rallies are sometimes equipped with an auxiliary spotlight, sometimes called an "alley light", in a swivel-mounted housing attached to one or both A-pillars, aimed by a handle protruding through the pillar into the vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity devices are lights and reflectors that are intended to make a vehicle more conspicuous and visible with respect to its presence, position, direction of travel, change in direction, or deceleration.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Such lights may light steadily, blink, or flash, depending on their intended and regulated function.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Most must be fitted in pairs—one left and one right—though some vehicles have multiple pairs (such as two left and two right stop lights) and/or redundant light sources (such as one left and one right stop light, each containing two bulbs).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Front position lights (known as parking lights in North America and front sidelights in the UK) provide nighttime standing-vehicle conspicuity.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They are designed to use little electricity so they can be left on when parked for prolonged periods of time.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Despite the UK term, these are not the same as the side marker lights described below.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The front position lights on any vehicle must emit white light, with the exception of motorcycles, which may have amber front position lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, Canada, Mexico, Iceland, Japan, New Zealand, and Australia (only if combined with a side marker), South Korea, North Korea, Vietnam, China, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, and much of the Middle East, they may emit amber light on any vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The "city light" terminology for front position lights derives from the practice, formerly adhered to in cities like Moscow, London and Paris, of driving at night in urban areas using these low-intensity lights rather than the vehicle's headlights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In Germany, the StVZO (Road Traffic Licensing Regulations) calls for a different function provided by these lights: with the vehicle's ignition switched off, the operator may activate a low-intensity white light at the front and red light at the rear on either the left or right side.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This function is used when parking in narrow unlit streets to provide parked-vehicle conspicuity to approaching drivers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This function, which is optional under UN and US regulations, is served passively in the United States by mandatory side marker retroreflectors.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some countries permit or require vehicles to be equipped with daytime running lights (DRLs).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the regulations of the country for which the vehicle is built, these may be functionally dedicated lights, or the function may be provided by the low beam or high beam headlights, the front turn signals, or the front fog lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Passenger cars and small delivery vans first type approved to UN Regulation 48 on or after 7 February 2011, and large vehicles (trucks and buses) type approved since August 2012, must be equipped with DRLs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Functional piggybacking, such as using the headlights, front turn signals, or fog lights as DRLs, is not permitted; the EU Directive requires functionally specific daytime running lights compliant with UN Regulation 87 and mounted to the vehicle in accord with UN Regulation 48.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Prior to the DRL mandate, countries requiring daytime lights permitted low beam headlights to provide that function.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] National regulations in Canada, Sweden, Norway, Slovenia, Finland, Iceland, and Denmark require hardwired automatic DRL systems of varying specification.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] DRLs are permitted in many countries where they are not required, but prohibited in other countries not requiring them.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Front, side, and rear position lights are permitted, required, or forbidden to illuminate in combination with daytime running lights, depending on the jurisdiction and the DRL implementation.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Likewise, according to jurisdictional regulations, DRLs mounted within a certain distance of turn signals are permitted or required to extinguish or dim down to parking light intensity individually when the adjacent turn signal is operating.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 87 stipulates that DRLs must emit white light with an intensity of at least 400 candela on axis and no more than 1200 candela in any direction.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, daytime running lights may emit either amber or white light, and may produce up to 7,000 candela.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This has provoked a large number of complaints about glare.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] UK regulations briefly required vehicles first used on or after 1 April 1987 to be equipped with a "dim-dip" device or special low-intensity running lights, except such vehicles as complying fully with UN Regulation 48 regarding the installation of lighting equipment.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] A dim-dip device operates the dipped beam headlights at between 10% and 20% of normal low-beam intensity.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Running lights permitted as an alternative to dim-dip were required to emit at least 200 candela straight ahead, and no more than 800 candela in any direction.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In practice, most vehicles were equipped with the dim-dip option rather than dedicated running lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The dim-dip systems were not intended for daytime use as DRLs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather, they operated if the engine was running *and* the driver switched on the position lights (called sidelights in the UK).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The UK was the only country to require such dim-dip systems, though vehicles so equipped were sold in other Commonwealth countries with left-hand traffic.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1988, the European Commission successfully prosecuted the UK government in the European Court of Justice, arguing that the UK requirement for dim-dip was illegal under EC directives prohibiting member states from enacting vehicle lighting requirements not contained in pan-European EC directives.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] As a result, the UK requirement for dim-dip was quashed.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Nevertheless, dim-dip systems remain permitted, and while such systems are not presently as common as they once were, dim-dip functionality was fitted on many new cars well into the 1990s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States, amber front and red rear side marker lights and retroreflectors are required.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The law initially required lights *or* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1968.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This was amended to require lights *and* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1970.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These side-facing devices make the vehicle's presence, position and direction of travel clearly visible from oblique angles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The lights are wired to illuminate whenever the vehicles' parking lights and tail lights are on, including when the headlights are being used.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Front amber side markers in the United States may be wired to flash in synchronous phase or opposite-phase with the turn signals; nevertheless, they are not required to flash at all.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Side markers are permitted but not required on cars and light passenger vehicles outside the United States and Canada.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These were sometimes used in tandem with fender lights during the same time period, when fenders were separate from the body and only covered the wheels.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They are activated by the driver on one side of the vehicle at a time to advertise intent to turn or change lanes towards that side, or used simultaneously as a hazard warning signal to warn other drivers of a vehicle parked on the road (see below).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] For many years, turn signals' on-off operation was activated by a thermal flasher unit which used a heating element, leaf spring, and a bimetallic strip.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] When activated by the stalk switch on the steering column, the signal lights and heating element turned on.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The heat caused the bimetallic strip to bend such that it threw the leaf spring over centre, opening the circuit and breaking power to the heating element and the signal lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] When the bimetallic strip cooled down, it would pull the leaf spring back over centre in the other direction, closing the contacts and again sending power to the lights and heating element.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The cycle would repeat until the power to the thermal flasher was switched off by the stalk switch.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Thermal flashers gradually gave way to electromechanical relays; one of many control strategies with relay-type flashers is to use a relaxation oscillator chip to generate square waves to the relay coil, causing the relay contacts to open and close.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern cars now use a relaxation oscillator and solid-state relay built into the body control module to flash the lights, and use speakers to produce the distinctive clicking sound associated with turn signals, which was previously made by a relay or the leaf spring in a thermal flasher.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] If the stalk switch is not moved beyond the fixed left/right position and allowed to flip back, the control module will only flash the lights three times.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Electric turn signal lights date from as early as 1907.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1908, Alfredo Barrachini in Rome added electric lights inside the arms that turned on as they extended, but operation was still by a cable system.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] An early patent for a new style of turn signal was issued in 1909 to a British man named Percy Douglas-Hamilton, who came up with a system that used a hand on each side of the car, which could be illuminated to indicate a coming turn.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Silent film star Florence Lawrence is also credited with introducing an innovative version of the signalling arm in 1914, a predecessor to the modern turn signal, and a mechanical brake signal.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] She did not patent these inventions, however, and received no credit or profit from them.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Possibly the first factory installation of illuminated turn signals was on the Talbot 105 (as well as the 75 and 95), which used them at the front as well as at the rear from 1932 until 1935.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The modern flashing turn signal was patented in 1938, and shortly after, most major automobile manufacturers offered this optional feature before it became mandatory in 1967.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] As of 2013, most countries require turn signals on all new vehicles that are driven on public roadways.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Alternative systems of hand signals were used earlier and remain common for bicycles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Hand signals are also sometimes used when regular vehicle lights are malfunctioning or for older vehicles without turn signals.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some cars from about 1900 to through 1966 used retractable semaphores called trafficators rather than flashing lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They were commonly mounted high up behind the front doors and swung out to a horizontal position.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They were fragile and could be easily broken off, and also had a tendency to stick in the closed or open position.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They could be fitted with a fixed or flashing light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] After turn signals were introduced regulations were brought in requiring them and laying out specifications that had to be met.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In most countries, cars must be equipped with side-mounted turn signal repeaters to make the turn indication visible laterally (i.e. to the sides of the vehicle) rather than just to the front and rear of the vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These are permitted, but not required in the United States and Canada.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] As an alternative in both the United States and Canada, the front amber side marker lights may be wired to flash with the turn signals, but this is not mandatory.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Mercedes-Benz introduced side turn signal repeaters integrated into the side-view mirrors in 1998, starting with its facelifted E-Class (W210).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Since then, many automakers have been incorporating side turn signal devices into the mirror housings rather than mounting them on the vehicle's fenders.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some evidence suggests that mirror-mounted turn signals may be more effective than fender-mounted ones.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are required to blink on and off, or "flash", at a steady rate of between 60 and 120 pulses per minute (1–2 Hz).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations require that all turn signals flash in simultaneous phase; US regulations permit side marker lights wired for side turn signal functionality to flash in opposite-phase.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] An audio and/or visual tell-tale indicator is required, to advise the driver when the turn signals are activated and operating.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This usually takes the form of one green light on the dashboard on cars from the 1950s or older, or two green indicator lights on cars from the 1960s to the present, and a rhythmic ticking sound generated electromechanically or electronically by the flasher.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] It is also required that the vehicle operator be alerted by much faster- or slower-than-normal flashing in the event a turn signal light fails.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are, in almost every case, activated by a horizontal stalk protruding from the side of the steering column, though on some vehicles it protrudes from the dashboard.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The driver raises or lowers the outboard end of the stalk in accord with the clockwise or anticlockwise direction the steering wheel is about to be turned.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In left-hand drive vehicles, the turn indicator stalk is usually located to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In right-hand-drive vehicles, there is less consistency; it may be located to the left or to the right of the steering wheel.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations do not specify a mandatory location for the turn signal control, only that it be visible and operable by the driver, and—at least in North America—that it be labelled with a specific symbol if it is not located on the left side of the steering column.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The international UN Regulations do not include analogous specifications.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Virtually all vehicles (except many motorcycles and commercial semi-tractors) have a turn indicator self-cancelling feature that returns the lever to the neutral (no signal) position as the steering wheel approaches the straight-ahead position after a turn has been made.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Beginning in the late 1960s, using the direction-indicator lights to signal for a lane change was facilitated by the addition of a spring-loaded momentary signal-on position just shy of the left and right detents.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The signal operates for however long the driver holds the lever partway towards the left or right turn signal detent.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have an automatic lane-change indication feature; tapping the lever partway towards the left or right signal position and immediately releasing it causes the applicable turn indicators to flash three to five times.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some transit buses, such as those in New York, have turn signals activated by floor-mounted momentary-contact footswitches on the floor near the driver's left foot (on left-hand drive buses).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The foot-activated signals allow bus drivers to keep both hands on the steering wheel while watching the road and scanning for passengers as they approach a bus stop.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] New York City Transit bus drivers, among others, are trained to step continuously on the right directional switch while servicing a bus stop, to signal other road users they are intentionally dwelling at the stop, allowing following buses to skip that stop.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This method of signalling requires no special arrangements for self-cancellation or passing.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Sequential turn signals are a feature on some cars, wherein the turn signal function is provided by multiple lit elements that illuminate sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The visual effect is one of outward motion in the direction of the intended turn or lane change.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The earlier, fitted to the 1965 through 1968 Ford-built cars and the 1971–1972 Nissan Cedric, employed an electric motor driving, through reduction gearing, a set of three slow-turning cams.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These cams would actuate switches to turn on the lights in sequence.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Later Ford cars and the 1969 Imperial used a transistorised control module with no moving parts to wear, break, or go out of adjustment.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] FMVSS 108 has been officially interpreted as requiring all light sources in an active turn signal to illuminate simultaneously.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles, such as the 2010 and later Ford Mustang, are designed such that the first lit segment of the multi-unit light is considered as the official turn signal, with the segments illuminated afterward considered as auxiliary lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Other US vehicles with sequential turn signals comply by illuminating all elements of the turn signal simultaneously, before sequentially turning them off.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Until the early 1960s, most front turn signals worldwide emitted white light and most rear turn signals emitted red light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Currently, most countries outside the United States and Canada require that all front, side and rear turn signals produce amber light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In Belgium, Brazil, Canada, the GCC countries, Israel, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and the US, the rear signals may be amber or red.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Additionally, red turn signals can also be found in countries with trade agreements with the US such as Mexico and South Korea, and New Zealand.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of red rear turn signals have claimed that they are less costly to manufacture, and automakers use the turn signal colour as a styling element to differentiate vehicles of different model years.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of amber rear turn signals say they are more easily discernible as turn signals.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] It has been recognised since the 1960s that amber turn signals are more quickly spotted than red ones.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] There is some evidence that turn signals with colourless clear lenses and amber bulbs may be less conspicuous in bright sunlight than those with amber lenses and colourless bulbs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The amber bulbs commonly used in turn signals with colourless lenses are no longer made with cadmium glass, since various regulations worldwide, including the European RoHS directive, banned cadmium because of its toxicity.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Amber glass made without cadmium is relatively costly, so most amber bulbs are now made with clear glass dipped in an amber coating.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] With accumulated heat-cool cycles, though, some of these coatings may flake off the bulb glass, or the colour may fade.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This causes the turn signal to emit white light rather than the required amber light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The international regulation on motor vehicle bulbs requires manufacturers to test bulbs for colour endurance.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] However, no test protocol or colour durability requirement is specified.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Discussion is ongoing within the *Groupe des Rapporteurs d'Éclairage*, the UNECE working group on vehicular lighting regulation, to develop and implement a colour durability standard.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather than using an amber bulb, some signal lights contain an inner amber plastic enclosure between a colourless bulb and the colourless outer lens or by using integrated amber LEDs in a colourless enclosure which produces less heat.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity for the rear of a vehicle is provided by rear position lights (also called tail lights).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These are required to produce only red light and to be wired such that they are lit whenever the front position lights are lit, including when the headlights are on.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear position lights may be combined with the vehicle's stop lights or be separate from them.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In combined-function installations, the lights produce brighter red light as stop lights and dimmer red light as rear position lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide stipulate minimum intensity ratios between the bright (stop) and dim (position) modes, so that a vehicle displaying rear position lights will not be mistakenly interpreted as showing stop lights and vice versa.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Red steadily lit rear lights, brighter than the rear position lights, are activated when the driver applies the vehicle's brakes and warn vehicles behind to prepare to stop.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These are formally called "stop lamps" in technical standards and regulations and in the Vienna Convention on Road Traffic, though they are often informally called brake lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They are required to be fitted in multiples of two, symmetrically at the left and right edges of the rear of every vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] 7 specify a range of acceptable intensity for a stop light of 60 to 185 candela.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where the UN regulations are not recognised, the acceptable range for a single-compartment stop light is 80 to 300 candela.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and Canada since 1986, in Australia and New Zealand since 1990, and in Europe and other countries applying UN Regulation 48 since 1998, a central stop (brake) light mounted higher than the vehicle's left and right stop lights is also required.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The so-called "centre high mount stop lamp", or **CHMSL** (pronounced /ˈtʃɪmzəl/), is sometimes informally called the "centre brake light", the "third brake light", the "eye-level brake light", the "safety brake light", or the "high-level brake light".
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL may use one or more filament bulbs or LEDs, or a strip of neon tubing as its light source.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is intended to provide a warning to drivers whose view of the vehicle's left and right stop lights is blocked by interceding vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] It also provides a redundant stop light signal in the event of a stop light malfunction.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where rear turn signals are permitted to emit red light, the CHMSL also helps to differentiate brake lights from rear position lights and turn signal lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] On passenger cars, the CHMSL may be placed above the back glass, affixed to the vehicle's interior just inside the back glass, or integrated into the vehicle's deck lid or into a spoiler.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Other specialised fitments are sometimes seen; the Jeep Wrangler and Land Rover Freelander have the CHMSL on a stalk fixed to the spare wheel carrier.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Trucks, vans, and commercial vehicles sometimes have the CHMSL mounted to the trailing edge of the vehicle's roof.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is required by regulations worldwide to be centred laterally on the vehicle, though UN Regulation 48 permits lateral offset of up to 15 cm if the vehicle's lateral centre is not coincident with a fixed body panel, but instead separates movable components such as doors.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Such an offset can be seen on the third-generation Renault Master and first-generation Ford Transit Connect vans.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The height of the CHMSL is also regulated, both in absolute terms and with respect to the mounting height of the vehicle's conventional left and right stop lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the left and right lights' height, the lower edge of the CHMSL may be just above the left and right lights' upper edge.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1952 Volkswagen Bus was equipped with only one stop light, mounted centrally and higher than the left and right rear lights, which did not produce a stop light function.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1968–1971 Ford Thunderbird could be ordered with optional supplemental high-mounted stop and turn signal lights integrated into the left and right interior trim surrounding the rear glass.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The Oldsmobile Toronado (from 1971 to 1978) and the Buick Riviera (from 1974 to 1976) had similar dual high-mounted supplemental stop/turn lights as standard equipment; these were located on the outside of the vehicle below the bottom of the rear glass.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of configuration was not widely adopted at the time.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Car and lighting manufacturers in Germany experimented with dual high-mount supplemental stop lights in the early 1980s, but this effort, too, failed to gain wide popular or regulatory support.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Effective with the 1986 model year, the United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada mandated that all new passenger cars come equipped with a CHMSL.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The requirement was extended to light trucks and vans for the 1994 model year.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Early studies involving taxicabs and other fleet vehicles found that a third high-level stop light reduced rear-end collisions by about 50%.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Once the novelty effect wore off as most vehicles on the road came to be equipped with a CHMSL, the crash-avoidance benefit declined.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] However, said benefit has not declined to zero, and a CHMSL has become so inexpensive to incorporate into a vehicle that it remains a cost-effective collision avoidance feature even at the long-term enduring crash-reduction benefit of 4.3%.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] A NHTSA report suggests that a vehicle equipped with a CHMSL has 23.7% less risk to be involved as a lead vehicle in a chain collision and 16.0% less risk to be involved as a middle vehicle in such a collision.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency stop signalling is a lighting function wherein the vehicle's stop (brake) lights and/or hazard/turn indicators flash in phase at 3 to 5 Hz under heavy or urgent braking.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The emergency stop signal is automatically activated if the vehicle speed is greater than 50 km/h (31 mph) and the emergency braking logic defined by regulation No.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In February 2019, members of the European Parliament approved rules making emergency stop signals mandatory on new vehicles sold in the European Union.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Toyota, Mercedes-Benz, Volvo and BMW were among the earlier automakers to begin equipping vehicles with ESS.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2013, Kia introduced the concept on some of their Australian-market models.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Other methods of severe braking indication have also been implemented; some Volvo models make the stop lights brighter, and some BMWs have "Adaptive Brake Lights" that effectively increase the size of the stop lights under severe braking by illuminating them at brighter-than-normal intensity.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] As long as the brighter-than-normal stop lights are within the regulated maximum intensity for stop lights in general, this kind of implementation does not require specific regulatory approval, since the stop lights continue to operate in accord with general stop light regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The idea behind such emergency braking indicator systems is to catch following drivers' attention with increased urgency.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] However, there remains considerable debate over whether the system offers a measurable increase in safety.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] To date, studies of vehicles with ESS have not shown significant improvement.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The systems used by BMW, Volvo, and Mercedes differ not only in operational mode (growing vs. intensifying vs. flashing, respectively), but also in such parameters as the deceleration threshold of activation.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Data is being collected and analyzed in an effort to determine how such a system might be implemented to maximize a safety benefit, if such a benefit can be realized with visual emergency braking displays.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] An experimental study at the University of Toronto has tested stop lights which gradually and continuously grow in illuminated area with increasing braking.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The ESS is not expensive because it reuses existing warning and stop signals.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] One potential problem with flashing stop lights in the United States and Canada is regulations that permit flashing stop lights to be used as rear turn signal and hazard lights, in lieu of separate dedicated lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In Europe and other countries adhering to UN Regulation 48, vehicles must be equipped with one or two bright red "rear fog lamps", which serve as high-intensity rear position lights to be activated in poor visibility conditions to make the vehicle more visible from the rear.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The allowable range of intensity for a rear fog light is 150 to 300 candela, within the range of a US stop light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear fog lights are not required equipment in the US, but they are permitted, and they are found almost exclusively on European-brand vehicles in North America.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Audi, Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, Mini, Land Rover, Porsche, Saab, and Volvo provide functional rear fog lights on their North American models.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles from non-European brands which are adaptions of European-market offerings, such as the first-generation Ford Transit Connect, have come standard with rear fog lights, or vehicles with European-market counterparts, such as the second generation Chrysler 300, have an option for them.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The second generation Oldsmobile Aurora also had dual rear fog lights installed in the rear bumper as standard equipment.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Most jurisdictions permit rear fog lights to be installed either singly or in pairs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] If a single rear fog is fitted, most jurisdictions require it to be located at or to the driver's side of the vehicle's centreline—whichever side is the prevailing driver's side in the country in which the vehicle is registered.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This is to maximise the sight line of following drivers to the rear fog light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In many cases, a single reversing light is mounted on the passenger side of the vehicle, positionally symmetrical with the rear fog.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] If two rear fog lights are fitted, they must be symmetrical with respect to the vehicle's centreline.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of twin rear fog lights say two lights provide vehicle distance information not available from a single light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of the single rear fog light say dual rear fog lights closely mimic the appearance of illuminated stop lights (which are mandatorily installed in pairs), reducing the conspicuity of the stop lights' message when the rear fogs are activated.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] To provide some safeguard against rear fog lights being confused with stop lights, UN Regulation 48 requires a separation of at least 10 cm between the closest illuminated edges of any stop light and any rear fog light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] To warn adjacent vehicle operators and pedestrians of a vehicle's rearward motion, and to provide illumination to the rear when reversing, each vehicle must be equipped with one or two rear-mounted, rear-facing reversing (or "backup") lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Reversing lights are required to produce white light by US and international UN regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] However, some countries have at various times permitted amber reversing lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, for example, vehicle manufacturers were faced with the task of localizing American cars originally equipped with combination red brake/turn signal lights and white reversing lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Both countries now require white reversing lights, and the combination amber turn/reverse light is no longer permitted on new vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The US state of Washington currently permits reversing lights to emit white or amber light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some car models, such as some Saabs have white reversing lights in the front turn indicators that switch on with the rear reversing lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The rear registration plate is illuminated either by a single or a pair of yellow or white light(s), affixed within the indentation of the trunk or bumper.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] It is designed to light the surface of the plate without creating light directly visible to the rear of the vehicle, and must be illuminated whenever the position lights are lit.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Large vehicles such as trucks and buses are in many cases required to carry additional lighting devices beyond those required on passenger vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The specific requirements vary according to the regulations in force where the vehicle is registered.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US and Canada, vehicles over 80 inches (2.032 m) wide must be equipped with three amber front and three red rear identification lights spaced 6–12 inches (15–30 cm) apart at the centre of the front and rear of the vehicle, as high as practicable.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The front identification lights are typically mounted atop the cab of the vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The purpose of these lights is to alert other drivers to the presence of a wide (and usually tall) vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 48 requires vehicles exceeding 2.10 metres (83 in) in width to be equipped with white front and red rear end-outline marker lights on both the left and right, which, like North American identification lights, are intended to indicate a vehicle's overall width and height.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The front clearance lights may be amber in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] US and Canadian regulations require large vehicles to be equipped with amber side marker lights and reflectors mounted midway between the front and rear side markers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Australian Design Rule 45/01 provides for side marker lights on trucks and other large vehicles producing amber light to the front and red to the rear with no requirement to emit light to the side.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Until about the 1970s in France, Spain, Morocco, and possibly other countries, many commercial vehicles and some Soviet Sovtransavto road trains had a green light mounted on the rear offside.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This could be operated by the driver to indicate that it was safe for the following vehicle to overtake.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The hazard warning signal (sometimes called "hazard warning flashers", "hazard warning lights", "emergency lights", "4-way flashers", "hazards", or "flashers") is provided by flashing all of a vehicle's left and right turn signals simultaneously and in phase.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Hazard warning signals first appeared as aftermarket accessories in the early 1950s; by the late 1960s, regulations around the world came to require all new vehicles to be so equipped.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Operation of the warning signals must be from a control independent of the turn signal control, and an audiovisual tell-tale must be provided to the driver.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In most vehicles, the hazard warning signals can be switched on and off with a physical push-button, which is typically marked with a triangular symbol, symbolizing a warning triangle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with separate left and right green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, both left and right indicators may flash to provide a visual indication of the hazard flashers' operation.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with a single green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, a separate red tell-tale must be provided for hazard flasher indication.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Because the hazard flasher function operates the vehicle's left and right turn signals, a left or a right turn signal function may not be provided while the hazard flashers are operating.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Apart from its use as emergency lighting, a single flash of the hazard lights is used to show gratitude to yielding drivers in several countries.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] However, in the United Kingdom, they must not be used except to warn others of either a temporary obstruction when the vehicle is stationary or a hazard ahead on a dual carriageway with a speed limit of at least 50 mph.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] "Retroreflectors" (also called "reflex reflectors") produce no light of their own, but rather reflect incident light towards its source, such as another driver's headlights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They are regulated as automotive lighting devices, and specified to account for the separation between a vehicle's headlights and its driver's eyes.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Thus, vehicles can remain conspicuous even with their lights off.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide require all vehicles and trailers to be equipped with rear-facing red retroreflectors; in countries where UN Regulation No.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] 48 is applied, these must be triangular on trailers and non-triangular on vehicles other than trailers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Since 1968, US regulations also require side-facing retroreflectors, amber in front and red in the rear.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Sweden, South Africa, and other countries have at various times required white front-facing retroreflectors.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations explicitly permit vehicle signal lights with intensity automatically increased during bright daylight hours when sunlight reduces the effectiveness of the stop lights, and automatically decreased during hours of darkness when glare could be a concern.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations in the US and by the UN contain provisions for determining the minimum and maximum acceptable intensity for lights that contain more than a single light source.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some jurisdictions, such as the US states of Washington, Oregon and Idaho, permit vehicles to be equipped with auxiliary rear signal systems displaying a green light when the accelerator is depressed, yellow light when the vehicle is coasting, and red light when the brake is depressed.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Such systems have in the past been sold as aftermarket accessories, but are today seldom seen in traffic.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Since the late 1960s, there have been proposals to introduce a front-mounted brake light, where green or blue lights would indicate to pedestrians at crossings that an approaching vehicle is slowing down.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] A small subjective survey was undertaken in the US in 1971.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2014, the idea was suggested by Slovak Lubomír Marjak (of manufacturing company Lumaco, which makes front brake lights) to German EU parliamentarian Dieter-Lebrecht Koch.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Field tests were done in Germany in 2017, as well as in Slovakia in 2022 and 2023.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Expert analysts have found severe flaws in these tests and the accompanying safety claims.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The only production car to feature a built-in front brake light (as of 2023) was the Bricklin SV-1 of 1974.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, among other bodies, has commissioned studies of vehicle signal systems and configurations to determine the most promising avenues and best practices for enhanced crash avoidance via optimized vehicle conspicuity and signal lighting systems.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Most cars have at least one "dome light" (or "courtesy light") located in or near the ceiling of the passenger compartment, to provide illumination by which to fasten seatbelts and enter or exit the car.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These often have an option to automatically switch on when the front (or any) passenger doors are opened.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Many vehicles have expanded this feature, causing the overhead interior light to remain on after all doors are closed, allowing passengers to fasten seat belts with added illumination.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The extended lighting cycle usually ends when the vehicle's ignition has begun, or a gradual reduction in light emitted after a couple of minutes if the car is not started, called "theater" lighting.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Interior lighting has been added on some vehicles at the bottom edge of the dashboard, illuminating the floor for front passengers, or underneath the front seats at the rear, illuminating the floor for rear passengers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of convenience lighting approach is also sometimes used to illuminate interior or exterior door handles, exterior step running boards, or electric window switches.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] LED light sources appear increasingly as interior convenience lights in various locations, especially with finely focused lighting on console control surfaces and in cabin storage areas.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Map lights are aimed at specific passenger positions and allow for reading without glare distraction to the driver.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have "approach lighting" or "puddle lights" (lights that illuminate the ground outside the doors) in the exterior mirrors or lower edges of the doors, as well as interior lighting activated via key fob.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Many cars have lights in the trunk, the engine compartment, the glove box, and other storage compartments.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern pickup trucks usually have one or more white cargo lights that illuminate the bed of the truck, often controlled in conjunction with the interior dome lighting.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Most gauges and controls on a dashboard in modern vehicles are illuminated when the headlights are turned on, and the intensity of light can be adjusted by the driver for comfort.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Saab automobiles, for example, have an aircraft-style "night panel" function that shuts off all interior illumination save for the speedometer (unless attention is called to a critical situation on another gauge) to improve the driver's night vision.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency vehicles such as fire engines, ambulances, police cars, snow-removal vehicles and tow trucks are usually equipped with intense warning lights of particular colours.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] These may be motorised rotating beacons, xenon strobes, or arrays of LEDs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] The prescribed colours differ by jurisdiction; in most countries, blue and red special warning lights are used on police, fire, and medical-emergency vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and some other jurisdictions, amber lights are for tow trucks, private security personnel, construction vehicles, and other nonofficial special-service vehicles, while volunteer firefighters use red, blue, or green, depending on jurisdiction.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US it is a violation of the DOT (Department of Transportation) Uniform Vehicle Code for any non-emergency vehicle (Police/Fire/Ambulance) to operate forward-facing red lights of any kind.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Some US states allow emergency vehicles to have blue lights that can be turned on to warn drivers of an emergency vehicle in action; blue and red lights can be combined, forward- and/or rear-facing.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] In the UK, doctors may use green warning lights; although these do not allow the user to claim any exemption from road traffic regulations (compared to the blue lights used by statutory emergency services when responding to calls).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Special warning lights, usually amber, are also sometimes mounted on slow or wide vehicles such as mobile cranes, excavators, tractors, and even mobility scooters in certain conditions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Standard taxicabs for street hire are distinguished by special lights affixed to the vehicle's roof in accordance with local regulations.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] They may have an illuminated "Taxi" sign, a light to signal that they are ready to take passengers, or off duty, or an emergency panic light the driver can activate in the event of a robbery to alert passersby to call the police.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on local regulations, the "Taxi" sign may also be required to display a number identifying the vehicle.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The incandescent light bulb was for a long time the only light source used in automotive lighting.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Incandescent bulbs are still commonly used in turn signals to stop hyper-flashing of the turn signal flashers.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Standardized type numbers are used by manufacturers to identify bulbs with the same specifications.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Bases may be bayonet-type with one or two contacts, plastic or glass wedges, or dual wire loops or ferrules used on tubular "festoon" lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Screw-base lights are never used in automobile applications due to their loosening under vibration.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Signal lights with internal or external coloured lenses use colourless bulbs; conversely, lights with colourless lenses may use red or amber bulbs to provide light of the required colours for the various functions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Tungsten-halogen lights are a very common light source for headlights and other forward illumination functions.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Some recent vehicles use small halogen bulbs for exterior signalling and marking functions, as well.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The first halogen light approved for automotive use was the H1, which used 55 watts producing 1500 lumens and was introduced in Europe in 1962.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Since 1993, light-emitting diodes (LEDs) have increasingly been used in automotive lighting.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] They offer a very long service life, extreme vibration resistance, high colour durability, high efficiency (lumen/Watt) and can benefit from considerably more compact packaging compared to most bulb-type assemblies.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs also offer a potential safety benefit when employed in stop lights; when power is applied, they rise to full intensity approximately 250 milliseconds (¼ second) faster than incandescent bulbs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] This effectively instant rise time theoretically provides following drivers more time to react to the stop light signal, but has not been shown to make cars with LED stop lights less likely to be struck from behind.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs were first applied to automotive lighting in centre high-mount stop lamps (CHMSLs), beginning with the 1986 Chevrolet Corvette (C4).
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Adoption of LEDs for other signal functions on passenger cars is gradually increasing with demand for the technology and related styling updates.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The first car registered to drive on the road with full LED rear lights was Land Rover's LCV 2/3 concept car in the 1990s.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] At the time, the only light function that was difficult to reproduce was the reverse light, as white LEDs did not yet exist.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The reverse function was only achievable with the introduction of blue LEDs; by mixing red, green and blue LEDs in a defined distributed pattern behind a lens, white light was produced that conformed to the legal requirements of a reverse light.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The Maserati 3200GT, introduced in 1999, was the first production car to use full LED taillights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] In North America, the 2000 Cadillac Deville was the first passenger car with LED taillights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2002 Kia Opirus was an early adopter of LED front turn signals.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2007 Audi R8 used two strips of optically focused high-intensity LEDs for its daytime running lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Optional on the R8 outside North America were the world's first LED headlights, made by AL-Automotive Lighting.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The low and high beams, along with the position (parking) light and front turn signal, all use LEDs.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The Lexus LS 600h (XF40) features LED low beam, position and side marker lights in North America, and the 2009 Cadillac Escalade Platinum used LEDs for the low and high beams, as well as for the position and side marker lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W222) used entirely LED lights, even in the most basic trim level.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lights are used for flashing beacon lights on vehicles such as maintenance trucks.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Previously, traditional light sources required the engine to continue running to ensure that the battery would not become depleted if the lights were to be used for more than a few hours.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] The energy-efficient nature of LEDs allows them to continue flashing with the engine off.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lighting systems are sensitive to heat.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Due to the negative influences of heat on the stability of photometric performance and the light transmitting components, the importance of thermal design, stability tests, usage of low-UV-type LED modules and UV-resistance tests of internal materials has increased dramatically.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] For this reason, LED signal lights must remain compliant with the intensity requirements for the functions they produce after one minute and after thirty minutes of continuous operation.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] In addition, UN Regulation 112 contains a set of tests for LED modules, including colour rendering, UV radiation, and temperature stability tests.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] According to UN Regulations 112 and 123, mechanical, electromechanical or other devices for headlights must withstand endurance tests and function failure tests.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] High-intensity discharge, or HID lights, sometimes referred to as "xenon lights", are modified metal halide lights employing xenon fill gas.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Traditional HID lights, such as those used for general lighting, have a long warm-up time.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Headlights must provide light very shortly after they are turned on, and the xenon gas serves to reduce warm-up time.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon light tubes were introduced into series production for the centre high-mount stop light on the 1995 Ford Explorer.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Notable later uses included the 1998 Lincoln Mark VIII with a neon tube spanning the width of the trunk decklid, and the BMW Z8, which made extensive use of neon.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon lights offer the same nearly instant rise time as LEDs, but require a high-voltage ballast.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] In December 2023, Mercedes-Benz received approval in California and Nevada, the only states where it is legal to operate their self-driving vehicles, for turquoise lights in accordance with SAE standard J3134, to indicate to outside observers that the car's self-driving system is engaged.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Mercedes is the first car manufacturer to equip their self-driving vehicles with such lights.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] In distributive light systems, the light from a single source is sent via optical fibres or light guides to wherever it is needed in the automobile.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Light guides are commonly used to distributively light dashboard displays, and premium vehicles are beginning to use distributive systems for lighting such items as door locks, window controls, and cup holders.
[src:bristol-type-603/automotive-lighting-p03] Distributive exterior lighting has also been explored, with high-intensity central light sources.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The **Bedford CF** is a range of full-size panel vans produced by Bedford - the commercial vehicles division of Vauxhall.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The van was introduced in 1969 to replace the CA model, and was sized to compete directly with the Ford Transit, which had entered production four years earlier.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Its design was similar to its American counterpart, the Chevrolet Van (1971–1995).
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Bedford was a General Motors subsidiary, and in some markets outside the United Kingdom and Ireland the CF was sold through Opel dealers as the **Opel Bedford Blitz** from 1973 on when the original Opel Blitz was phased out.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] In other markets such as in Norway the CF retained its original name.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The CF was notable for being the last vehicle solely designed by Vauxhall when it was discontinued in 1986 (the last Vauxhall passenger car had been the HC Viva which had ceased production in 1979); with all Vauxhall cars by that point being essentially rebranded Opels.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The Bedford brand continued on certain badge engineered light vans and pick-ups from Isuzu and Suzuki, built under licence at the IBC Vehicles plant in Luton, before being retired in 1991 in favour of Vauxhall or Opel.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Introduced in November 1969 to replace the 17-year-old Bedford CA, the CF van variants soon became some of the most popular light commercial vehicles on British roads.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The CF could be specified with a hinged door in the side panel directly behind the passenger door, and it was generally with this layout that the van was also commonly used as a base vehicle for a caravanette.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The engine was the well-proven Slant Four engine which had been introduced for the Vauxhall FD Victor models in 1967.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Apart from an increased engine capacity from 1.6 L (1,598 cc) to 1.8 L (1,759 cc) and from 2.0 L (1,975 cc) to 2.3 L (2,279 cc) in 1972, the power units remained unchanged.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] A four-cylinder 1.8 L (1,760 cc) Perkins diesel engine could be specified for an extra £130 (1969), while a larger 2.5 L (2,523 cc) version was used for heavier versions.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] These units were rated at 50 and 61 PS (37 and 45 kW; 49 and 60 hp) DIN.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] In 1976, a 2.1 L (2,064 cc) overhead camshaft (OHC) diesel engine from Opel replaced the outdated Perkins units.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] In Australasian markets, the CF could be optioned with Holden six-cylinder units, in 2,850 cc (173.9 cu in) and 3,310 cc (202.0 cu in) forms.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] This was as an answer to the rival Ford Transit range, which in Australia used six-cylinder engines from the Ford Falcon.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The Bedford used the same basic suspension lay-out as the Vauxhall Victor, though married to greater wheel arch clearances and calibrated for greater weight carrying capacity.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The front independent suspension featured a double wishbone layout with coil springs and telescopic shock absorbers, while the rear wheels were suspended by a combination involving a live axle and traditional long single-leaf springs.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Several different manual transmissions were used: the Vauxhall three-speed, four-speed, Bedford four-speed, ZF four-speed, ZF five-speed, and the General Motors automatic.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The Laycock type of overdrive was available to order or on the later Vauxhall four-speed models.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] A standard panel van which was intended to rival the Ford Transit; the special van body (essentially a self-contained cab with a general-purpose chassis onto which a wide range of custom-built bodies or beds could be built), and the Dormobile (caravanette).
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The CF series 1 facelift was introduced in 1980, introducing the 2.3 L (2,260 cc) Opel 23D diesel engine with 61 hp (45.5 kW).
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Units exported to Germany (Bedford Blitz) received a smaller, 2.0 L (1,998 cc) diesel, producing 60 PS (44 kW; 59 hp).
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] This engine was also installed in many other export markets where tax categories suited engines with less than two litres of displacement, such as the Benelux countries and Finland.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The 1.8 and 2.3 litre petrol units remained the same.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The restyled front end was engineered so that by removing 8 bolts the whole front panel could be completely removed, providing easy access to the engine so it could be removed from the front instead of from underneath like on the CF1.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The CF1 "facelift" is often confused with being a CF2 because it's difficult to tell them apart from the exterior.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The easiest visual check is that the CF facelift will have the same old metallic door handles and mirrors as the CF1 while on the CF2 have new plastic ones.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] In 1984 the CF was renamed CF2 and basically only received mechanical upgrades.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The diesel engines remained the 2.3 (with the 2.0 available in continental Europe) but the old Vauxhall slant fours were replaced by a 2.0 L (1,979 cc), 78 hp (58 kW) version of the Opel CIH four cylinder.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] In 1985 the CF2 was sold side by side in UK with the Bedford Midi - a smaller, badge engineered version of the Isuzu Fargo which was locally built at the newly established IBC Vehicles venture with Isuzu.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] By then the CF's replacement was put on hold and then ultimately dropped when Bedford decided that rebadging other GM owned brands was much cheaper.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The last CF2s were sold in the UK in 1987 and marked the end of original Bedford designed vehicles.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] One noteworthy variant, the CF Electric was introduced in 1982.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] More than 100 prototypes were built and tested at Millbrook Proving Ground between 1977 and 1983.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] It was the first electrically powered vehicle planned for mass production based on a fossil fuel vehicle platform, built in partnership between Bedford, Lucas, Chloride Group and the UK government on a 5-year grant scheme.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Most were sold to government agencies, the Royal Mail, and local authorities for trials, which collectively were driven for more than 7,000,000 mi (11,000,000 km).
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] However, with a price tag much higher than a standard CF, and battery technology at the time not advancing quickly, Bedford cancelled the program in July 1986 after 300 to 475 vehicles had been built.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The government scheme wound down in 1987; the model was withdrawn and spares for it soon dried up.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] One of the prototypes was acquired and tested by Southern California Edison in 1980.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The lead-acid traction batteries were housed in a compartment below the floor and the DC traction motor was placed at the rear, coupled to a step down reduction gearbox attached to the CF's standard differential, but turned through 180°.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] There were 36 battery cells of 6 V each, wired in series for a total voltage of 216 V and storage capacity of 180 A-hr (38.9 kW-hr), with a total weight of 1,000 kg (2,205 lb); these required rewatering every two weeks, a procedure which took approximately three hours to complete.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The DC traction motor had a rated output of 37 kW (50 hp), with a weight of 142 kg (312 lb) and was made by Lucas, model MT286.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The motor control system was housed under the bonnet and a small diesel heater provided cabin heating.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The system also featured regenerative braking, however this could be turned off as it was found that in wet conditions the motor could lock the rear wheels up in a similar way as applying the handbrake.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] As tested in 1980, the prototype had a range which varied from 15 mi (24 km), fully loaded on steep hills, to 74 mi (119 km), on freeway routes with no payload, and a top speed of 54 mph (87 km/h) unladen.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] A heavily modified version of the CF Electric also was exported in left-hand drive form into the United States where it was rebadged and sold as the **GMC Griffon**.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] As tested in 1988, the Griffon weighed 3,073 kg (6,775 lb), with 1,100 kg (2,500 lb) of that being the weight of the battery pack.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] More than 30 of these vans were exported for trials with electric utility clients, in partnership with the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI), but ultimately, as with the British variant, these never were sold widely in the American market.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The Griffon was notable for being the first electric van sold by GM in the US, a market segment they would not re-enter until VIA Motors started converting Chevrolet Express vans into extended-range electric vehicles around 2014, which were marketed as the VTRUX Van.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] EPRI's work with the Griffon would lead to the G-Van of 1990, a variant of the conventional Chevrolet/GMC full-size vans retrofitted with the Griffon's powertrain, and later the Chrysler TEVan, which featured a longer range using nickel-iron battery chemistry.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The Bedford CF van was the second most popular van in the UK, second only to the Ford Transit.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Along with the Transit, the CF was usefully wider than competitor vehicles from Austin-Morris, Rootes and Volkswagen.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] It was also the most common caravanette.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] CFs were popular with customisers throughout the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] British police forces, in particular, used them for prisoner transport and as riot vans.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] They were also used by the Garda Síochána (Republic of Ireland police).
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Some ambulance services kept them in service for longer than usual after production ended as they were liked by crews.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] The British Military also had a fleet of CFs.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] They were used by builders and builders' merchants, as well as by courier services and the Post Office.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] They were also a popular caravanette due to their space and reasonable fuel consumption.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] They were used as ice cream vans in Britain and Australia.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] A heavily modified CF was used as the Mystery Machine in *Scooby-Doo: The Movie* 2002.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Initially, Bedford wanted to enter a joint venture with Leyland Motors to produce a replacement for the Bedford CF but these plans never caught on, since the British government did not want one of their major truck manufacturers to be controlled by a foreign company.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Following economic problems and declining sales by Bedford, it was decided to divest the once legendary company with the Luton plant being re-organized as a joint venture with Isuzu and renamed to IBC Vehicles while the Dunstable plant was sold to AWD Trucks.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] In 1986, the Isuzu Fargo started getting produced by IBC as the Bedford Midi with local modifications for the European market.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] GM Europe would not return in the large panel van market until 1997 and 1998 when production of the Renault-based Opel/Vauxhall Arena and Movano started, both of which serve as the true successors to the CF range.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Vauxhall continued to supply the CF's taillights to Bristol Cars for use in the Bristol Britannia until 2000.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] (2279 cc) Vauxhall low compression OHC engines introduced from chassis number 2V610007.
[src:bristol-type-603/bedford-cf] Opel 1979 cc CIH petrol engine replaced Vauxhall 1759 cc and 2239 cc OHC petrol engine.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] The **Bristol 400** is a luxury car made by the Bristol Cars division of the Bristol Aeroplane Company.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] Manufactured from 1947 to 1950, it was the first model of car that the company made.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] As World War II progressed, Bristol Aircraft considered its future, which resulted in forming a car division in 1945, later becoming the Bristol Cars company in its own right.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] Engineers from Bristol inspected the Soviet-controlled BMW factory at Eisenach in the Soviet occupation zone in Germany, and returned to Britain with plans for the BMW 327 and the BMW six-cylinder engine as official war reparations.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] Bristol then employed BMW engineer Fritz Fiedler to lead its engine development team.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] In 1946 Bristol Aircraft acquired a majority shareholding in Frazer Nash, which in the 1930s held a licence to build the BMW 328.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] In 1947 the newly-formed Bristol Cars released its 400 coupé.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] It is a lengthened version of the BMW 327, and features BMW's double-kidney radiator grille.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] Bristol based the 400 on the best features of two outstanding pre-war BMWs: the engine of the 328, and the chassis of the 326.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] These were covered with a mainly steel body but with aluminium bonnet, door and boot skins inspired by the 327.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] The 400 has a slightly modified version of BMW's six-cylinder pushrod engine of 1,971 cc (bore 66 mm, stroke 96 mm).
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] This engine, considered advanced for its time due to its hemispherical combustion chambers and very short inlet and exhaust ports, develops 80 horsepower at 4,500 rpm, and gives the car a top speed of about 148 km/h (92 mph), with acceleration to match.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] In order to form a hemispherical combustion chamber, the valves are positioned at an angle to the head.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] In order to drive both sets of valves from a single camshaft, the Bristol engine uses a system of rods, followers and bell-cranks to drive the valves on the far side of the engine from the camshaft.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] Owners soon found that setting and maintaining the numerous clearances in the system was difficult, but vital to keep the engine in tune.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] The gearbox is a four-speed manual with synchromesh on the upper three ratios and a freewheel in first.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] The 400 is the only Bristol that has a steel and aluminium skin.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] It has all flat glass, apart from the curved rear window, which is glazed in Perspex, and was available to specification with a top hinge.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] This was very welcome on warmer climate export markets, where the sliding door windows provided only marginal ventilation to the occupants.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] The 400 has independent front suspension with a transverse leaf spring and a live axle, located by an A-bracket over the differential case, and longitudinal torsion bars with transverse arms and brackets at the rear.
[src:bristol-type-603/bristol-400] It has a lengthy 2,895 mm (114.0 in) wheelbase and a very BMW-like grille at the front of its long bonnet.
